  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Maria Weston Chapman would rejoice to see Mrs. Lucretia Mott attend the New England Anti-Slavery Convention; she wants Lucretia to stay at the Chapman&apos;s house. Anne Warren Weston just returned from New York and reports &quot;a battle won.&quot; Chapman comments on Henry Brewster Stanton and his relation to Daniel Wise and Alanson St. Clair. Chapman comments: &quot;They are planning a new organizaton.&quot; Chapman compares the recognition of such an organization to the introduction of a new planet into the solar system. The assessment of $5000 has been pledged by the Massachusetts Society. &quot;But ought we to pay a cent ...?&quot; Elizur Wright is here to edit the Abolitionist newspaper.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">This letter was written on the blank pages of a circular (flier), a reproduced invitation to the New England Anti-Slavery Convention, dated Boston, May 13th, 1839.</subfield>
